.\" rdpsee - RDP server inspection tool (the observe companion to rdpdo)
.\" Generated from rdpsee command documentation
.TH RDPSEE 1 "June 2026" "rdpsee 1.1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
rdpsee \- RDP server inspection and reconnaissance tool
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B rdpsee
.RI [ OPTIONS ]
.I COMMAND
.RI [ TARGET ...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B rdpsee
inspects an RDP server and reports on it; unlike its companion
.BR rdpdo (1),
it never drives the session or injects input. It observes one of three
tiers of depth, from a connectionless pre-auth probe through a TLS handshake
to a fully completed session, and authenticates only where reading requires it.
.PP
One command runs per invocation:
.B rdpsee
.I COMMAND
.RI [ TARGET ...].
Global flags may appear anywhere on the command line.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-s " HOST" "\fR,\fP \-\-server " HOST
Server address (host or host:port, default port 3389). Not required for the
offline \fBhelp\fP command; \fBscan\fP can instead take targets positionally.
.TP
.BI \-u " USER" "\fR,\fP \-\-user " USER
RDP username. rdpsee observes pre-auth where the server allows it; credentials
are used only by \fBreport\fP and \fBshot\fP, and only to read.
.TP
.BI \-p " PASS" "\fR,\fP \-\-password " PASS
RDP password.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-nla
Disable NLA/CredSSP; use TLS-only.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-auth
Skip authentication entirely (for servers that allow anonymous connections).
.TP
.BI \-\-timeout " SECONDS"
Overall timeout (default: 30).
.TP
.BI \-\-width " PIXELS"
Desktop width requested during capability negotiation (default: 1920).
.TP
.BI \-\-height " PIXELS"
Desktop height requested during capability negotiation (default: 1080).
.TP
.B \-\-json
Emit machine-readable JSON. Honored by every command; \fBscan\fP always emits
an array.
.TP
.B \-\-verbose
Enable debug tracing to stderr.
.TP
.B \-\-ci
With \fBscan\fP, exit non-zero unless every target meets \fB\-\-expect\fP.
.TP
.BI \-\-expect " CAPS"
With \fBscan\fP \fB\-\-ci\fP, the comma-separated capabilities every target must
meet: reachable, tls, nla, egfx.
.SH COMMANDS
.SS Report
.TP
.BI scan " [TARGET...]" " [\-\-ci] [\-\-expect CAPS]"
Probe one or many servers' security posture pre-auth, with no login. Drives
only the X.224 security negotiation (RDP_NEG_REQ / RDP_NEG_RSP): no TLS
handshake, no MCS, no authentication. Reports reachability, the selected
security protocol (STANDARD_RDP_SECURITY, SSL/TLS, HYBRID, or HYBRID_EX),
whether NLA/CredSSP is required, and the pre-auth capability flags (EGFX,
restricted-admin, redirected-auth, extended-client-data). A rejected
negotiation is reported with its failure code (e.g. SSL_REQUIRED_BY_SERVER,
HYBRID_REQUIRED_BY_SERVER). Targets accept hostnames, host:port, and IPv4 CIDR
ranges (/16 to /32, capped at 65536 hosts), probed concurrently in input order.
A single target prints a detail block; multiple print a compact sweep table.
.TP
.B cert
Inspect a server's TLS certificate, no login required. Negotiates an
enhanced-security protocol and completes the TLS handshake without
authenticating, then reports the certificate: subject, issuer, self-signed
status, validity window, serial, signature and public-key algorithms, subject
alternative names, and the SHA-256 fingerprint of the certificate DER. Fails if
the server offers only standard RDP security.
.TP
.B id
Fingerprint a server. Negotiates TLS (no authentication) and derives a stable
JA4-style fingerprint of the server's configuration, alongside the certificate
SHA-256 (the exact-instance identity). See FINGERPRINT FORMAT below.
.TP
.BI shot " [PATH]"
Capture a screenshot of the server's current screen to PATH (default:
screenshot.png). Completes the connection (it needs decoded frames), polls for
real content for up to 10 seconds, then saves a PNG. With no credentials it
captures the login screen where the server allows it; with \fB\-u\fP/\fB\-p\fP
it captures the post-login desktop.
.TP
.B report
Connect and report basic capabilities: desktop size and graphics mode (EGFX vs
bitmap). Authenticates only if credentials are supplied. This is the default
action when no command is given. For pre-auth security detail across one or many
targets, prefer \fBscan\fP.
.SS Info & Diagnostics
.TP
.BI help " [COMMAND]"
Show help for all commands or a specific command. Does not require \fB\-s\fP.
.SH OBSERVATION TIERS
.TP
.B Connectionless (no auth)
.B scan
\(em X.224 security negotiation only.
.TP
.B TLS handshake (no auth)
.BR cert ", " id
\(em complete the TLS handshake, no CredSSP or session.
.TP
.B Completed session
.BR report ", " shot
\(em complete the connection; authenticate only with \fB\-u\fP/\fB\-p\fP.
.SH FINGERPRINT FORMAT
The
.B id
command produces a fingerprint of the form
.IR rdp_ <sec><caps>_<signing><key>/<hash> :
.TP
.I <sec>
Security tier: q=HYBRID_EX, h=HYBRID, s=SSL/TLS, r=standard-RDP.
.TP
.I <caps>
Capability flags, any of: g=EGFX, a=restricted-admin, d=redirected-auth,
e=extended-client-data (\- when none).
.TP
.I <signing>
S=self-signed, C=CA-signed.
.TP
.I <key>
Server key type: r=RSA, e=ECDSA, d=Ed25519, x=other.
.TP
.I <hash>
16 hex chars: a truncated SHA-256 over the raw protocol bits and certificate
algorithm OIDs, independent of name formatting.
.PP
Two servers with the same fingerprint share the same RDP security and capability
posture; an identical certificate SHA-256 means the same instance.
.SH TARGET FORMATS
.TP
.B Host
host \fRor\fP host:3389
.TP
.B IPv4 CIDR
10.0.0.0/24 (\fBscan\fP only, /16 to /32)
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success. With \fBscan \-\-ci\fP, every target also met \fB\-\-expect\fP.
.TP
.B 1
A failure, timeout, or an unmet \fB\-\-expect\fP.
.SH EXAMPLES
Probe a single server's pre-auth security posture:
.PP
.RS
rdpsee -s 192.168.1.10 scan
.RE
.PP
Sweep a subnet and gate in CI on enhanced security with NLA:
.PP
.RS
rdpsee scan 10.0.0.0/24 --ci --expect tls,nla
.RE
.PP
Inspect a server's certificate as JSON:
.PP
.RS
rdpsee -s host --json cert
.RE
.PP
Fingerprint a server:
.PP
.RS
rdpsee -s host id
.RE
.PP
Capture the post-login desktop:
.PP
.RS
rdpsee -s host -u user -p pass shot desktop.png
.RE
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR rdpdo (1),
.BR nmap (1),
.BR sslscan (1)
